1. Introduction
----------------------------------------------------------------------
PyDock is a set of tools for protein-protein docking. First version was 
written by Juan Fernandez-Recio in 2004.

2. Installation
----------------------------------------------------------------------

2.1. Setup
pyDock directory will look as below:
  
  |--data  	 -> data required by pyDock
  |--etc
  |--pydock.conf -> configuration file
  |--LICENSE     -> a copy of the license file
  |--README      -> this file
  |--pyDock3 	 -> pyDock binary

You can add pyDock3 to you path, e.g.: 
  In .bashrc, add the line:
  export PATH=$PATH:/path/to/pyDock3/

You will need extra software in order to properly execute all pyDock modules:

2.2. FTDock
pyDock can use FTDock program to generate docking poses (Note that FTDock is not
distributed in this package, you can find it at: http://www.sbg.bio.ic.ac.uk/docking/ftdock.html)
In pyDock configuration file (etc/pydock.conf) you can specify the path for
FTDock and in [ftdock] section parameters used.

2.3. ZDock
pyDock can use ZDock as well to generate docking poses. You will be able to download
ZDock at http://zlab.bu.edu/zdock.
Change pydock.conf file according to your installation path.

2.4 SCWRL
pyDock makes use of SCWRL software to rebuild missing side chains. You can find this software 
here: http://dunbrack.fccc.edu/scwrl4/


3. Tutorial and official documentation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Official documentation and tutorials can be found online at:

http://life.bsc.es/pid/pydock/doc/


